summary:
The Security Council,

Adopted resolution 1462 (2003) on 30 January 2003, 

Recalling its resolutions, particularly resolution 1427 (2002), and the report of the Secretary-General (S/2003/39),

 Condemns the lack of progress on the Abkhazia, Georgia conflict settlement, 

 Welcomes the contributions of UNOMIG and the CIS peacekeeping force,

1. Welcomes the Secretary-General's report; 

2. Reaffirms Georgia's sovereignty, independence and territorial integrity within recognized borders; 

3. Supports the Secretary-General's and his Special Representative's efforts, assisted by the Russian Federation, 

4. Backs the "Basic Principles for the Distribution of Competences between Tbilisi and Sukhumi"; 

5. Regrets the lack of progress on negotiations on Abkhazia's political status; 

6. Emphasizes that concessions from both sides are required; 

7. Urges the Abkhaz side to discuss the document; 

8. Notes the Secretary-General's intention to convene an informal brainstorming session; 

9. Urges parties to overcome mutual mistrust; 

10. Condemns ceasefire agreement violations; 

11. Welcomes decreased tensions in Kodori Valley; 

12. Requests Georgian side to improve security for joint patrols; 

13. Urges parties to revitalize the peace process.
